my_review:
It's a plain fantasy novel, but the most captivating book I've read in a while.

Every plot-twist was loaded and sprung just in time to keep you reading on to the next surprise. And the shtick of having the protagonist narrate his own story only added to the exceptional pacing.

It was thrilling, even though the plot was the same old 'magic boy saves the day' storyline.

Sometimes five stars aren't enough. I feel the need to demote all of my other ratings to grade this one appropriately.

It's an epic story, spanning multiple generations, about a small settlement in southern California and it's eclectic and colorful inhabitants.

Apparently it's non-fiction, a second-hand retelling of Steinbeck's family, but that seems to good to be true.

title: Inner Engineering: A Yogi's Guide to Joy
author: Sadhguru
my_review:
This once felt a touch too mystical, even for a hippie like yours truly. That said, I wouldn't be so quick to dismiss old Sadhguru.

The book's filled with incredible stories and anecdotes, usually followed by some profound lesson that's hard to disagree with, like:

"when pain, misery, or anger happen, it is time to look within you, not around you."

He's not wrong, but I wished he elaborated more, that he reasoned beyond the short and pithy maxims, but maybe that says more about me than the quality of the book.

title: Waking Up: A Guide to Spirituality Without Religion
author: Sam Harris
my_review:
If you've never dropped acid, or anything alike, I imagine you'd scoff or completely gloss over the book's premise, and no one could blame you. 'The self is an illusion.' It sounds absolutely absurd, but it's true.

It's so profound two of the world's leading religions were founded because of it, however, no book or religious manuscript can illuminate the premise like psychedelics slamming you flat on your ass do. Words cannot describe it. 'Nirvana', 'ego-death', 'the self is an illusion'; they just don't cut it, so don't fret if you don't get it. Maybe hit up your local contact.

If you have tried psychodelics, I think you'll find Harris's book to be an exceptionally articulate and surgical analysis of consciousness and this idea of the 'self', but beware, he does write like an academic.
